statement_latex:
Use the method of diagonalization to transform the following system of
equations into a decoupled one:

$\displaystyle x' = \begin{pmatrix}
4 & 2\\
2 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
x +
\begin{pmatrix}
t
e^{t^2}
\end{pmatrix}$

and you must explicitly calculate all matrices involved. Here

$\displaystyle x(t) = \begin{pmatrix}
x_1(t)\\
x_2(t)\end{pmatrix}
.$ You do not need to solve the system.

statement_raw:
Use the method of diagonalization to transform the following system of equations
into a decoupled one:

&lt;math> \displaystyle 
x' = \begin{pmatrix}
4 &amp; 2\\
2 &amp; 1
\end{pmatrix}
x +
\begin{pmatrix}
t
e^{t^2}
\end{pmatrix}
&lt;/math>

and you must explicitly calculate all matrices involved.
Here 

&lt;math> \displaystyle x(t) = \begin{pmatrix}
x_1(t)\\
x_2(t)\end{pmatrix}
. 
&lt;/math>
You do not need to solve the system.
